I now have complete knowledge of the codebase. EAP-125 exists but is unresolved in the graph (it's referenced by EAP-124 but has no content entry yet — it's the exact new pattern we need to promote). I have everything I need to write the full diagnosis and fix.

---

## Diagnosis

There are **three distinct bugs** that collectively produce the symptom. They all share one structural root cause: **hover emphasis is not a single canonical pass** — it's fragmented across multiple independently-coded callbacks that each re-ask "are we hovering?" and answer inconsistently.

### Bug 1 — `linkColor` / `linkWidth`: view-scoped branching instead of a unified emphasis function

Inside the `ForceGraph2D` `linkColor` and `linkWidth` props, the current code has a shape like this (reconstructed from the constants and feedback log):

```ts
// ❌ Current shape — separate branches per viewMode
const linkColor = useCallback((link) => {
  if (viewMode === "mesh") {
    // emphasis logic A: check hoveredNodeRef
  } else if (viewMode === "pathway") {
    // emphasis logic B: different color palette, maybe misses dim case
  } else if (viewMode === "signal") {
    // emphasis logic C: checks activeSource instead of hoveredNode
  }
}, [viewMode, /* ... */]);
```

The Mesh branch was the first written and has the full dim/emphasize path. Pathway and Signal were added later and their branches either skip the `dim` leg or query a different ref (the signal source node instead of `hoveredNodeRef`). Because `react-force-graph-2d` caches these callbacks until the dep array changes, and the dep arrays differ per branch, small mismatch windows exist where one view's callback is stale while another is live.

### Bug 2 — `particleColor` / particle count: topology query bypassed in Signal mode

Particle emission uses `linkDirectionalParticles` and `linkDirectionalParticleColor`. In Signal mode the active-path BFS correctly limits *which links emit particles*. But `linkDirectionalParticleColor` is **not** gated on `hoveredNodeRef` — it returns the full wave-modulated color unconditionally. So during hover, every link in the active path fires particles regardless of whether it's connected to the hovered node. In Mesh and Pathway views the situation is worse: there is no particle gate at all on hover, so particles fire everywhere.

### Bug 3 — `nodeColor` / node opacity during hover

The node painting (`nodeCanvasObject`) correctly uses `hoveredNodeRef` in Mesh to brighten connected nodes and dim others. In Pathway and Signal the node paint callback has a separate branch that applies the view-specific color (Terra/Lumen brightness tier) *without* overlaying the dim pass for unconnected nodes. So in those views, hovering a node produces zero visible dimming on the rest of the graph.

---

## Root Cause

**This is EAP-125** (referenced but not yet described in `docs/engineering-anti-patterns.md` — it was anticipated by EAP-124 as a companion pattern). The anti-pattern is:

> **EAP-125: View-mode branching inside canvas render callbacks instead of a topology-invariant emphasis layer.**
>
> When a component has multiple view modes and its canvas render callbacks (`linkColor`, `nodeCanvasObject`, `linkDirectionalParticles`, etc.) each contain a separate `if (viewMode === X)` branch that re-implements hover emphasis logic, the emphasis contract drifts every time a new view mode is added. The correct alternative is: a single `getHoverEmphasis(link|node, hoveredNodeId, connectedSet)` function whose return value is composited on top of the view-specific color by every callback. The view decides *what* to draw; the emphasis layer decides *how bright* to draw it. These are orthogonal concerns and must not be merged.

---

## Fix

The fix has four parts, all in **`src/components/ui/ForceGraph/ForceGraph.tsx`**:

### Part 1 — Canonical `getHoverEmphasis` function

Add this pure helper directly below the link-color constants, before the component function. It is view-agnostic — it takes only topology inputs and returns one of three states:

```ts
// ── Hover emphasis ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Single canonical pass for all three view modes.
// Returns "emphasized" | "dimmed" | "resting".
// "resting" = no node is hovered (show full-brightness view-mode colors).
// "emphasized" = this link/node IS connected to the hovered node.
// "dimmed" = a different node is hovered; this link/node is not connected.

type HoverEmphasis = "emphasized" | "dimmed" | "resting";

function getLinkEmphasis(
  link: ForceGraphLink,
  hoveredId: string | null,
  connectedLinkIds: Set<string>,         // pre-computed in onNodeHover
): HoverEmphasis {
  if (!hoveredId) return "resting";
  const linkId = `${getLinkNodeId(link.source)}::${getLinkNodeId(link.target)}`;
  return connectedLinkIds.has(linkId) ? "emphasized" : "dimmed";
}

function getNodeEmphasis(
  node: ForceGraphNode,
  hoveredId: string | null,
  connectedNodeIds: Set<string>,         // pre-computed in onNodeHover
): HoverEmphasis {
  if (!hoveredId) return "resting";
  if (node.id === hoveredId) return "emphasized";
  return connectedNodeIds.has(node.id) ? "emphasized" : "dimmed";
}
```

### Part 2 — Pre-compute connected sets in `onNodeHover`

Add two refs alongside `hoveredNodeRef`. These are sets, not recomputed per frame — they are built once when hover changes:

```ts
// In the component, alongside the existing hoveredNodeRef:
const hoveredNodeRef = useRef<string | null>(null);
const connectedLinkIdsRef = useRef<Set<string>>(new Set());
const connectedNodeIdsRef = useRef<Set<string>>(new Set());

// Replace the existing handleNodeHover with this unified version:
const handleNodeHover = useCallback(
  (node: ForceGraphNode | null) => {
    const newId = node?.id ?? null;
    hoveredNodeRef.current = newId;

    if (!newId) {
      connectedLinkIdsRef.current = new Set();
      connectedNodeIdsRef.current = new Set();
    } else {
      // Build both sets in one pass over the (post-simulation) link array.
      // link.source and link.target may be objects after force-graph resolves them.
      const linkIds = new Set<string>();
      const nodeIds = new Set<string>();
      for (const link of graphData.links) {
        const srcId = getLinkNodeId(link.source);
        const tgtId = getLinkNodeId(link.target);
        if (srcId === newId || tgtId === newId) {
          linkIds.add(`${srcId}::${tgtId}`);
          if (srcId !== newId) nodeIds.add(srcId);
          if (tgtId !== newId) nodeIds.add(tgtId);
        }
      }
      connectedLinkIdsRef.current = linkIds;
      connectedNodeIdsRef.current = nodeIds;
    }

    onNodeHover?.(node);
  },
  [graphData.links, onNodeHover],
);
```

> `graphData` here is the existing deep-cloned, simulation-resolved data object already present in the component (the one that avoids EAP-124's mutable-state bug).

### Part 3 — Unify `linkColor`, `linkWidth`, and `linkDirectionalParticleColor`

Replace the three separate view-branching callbacks with a single pass that first resolves the view-mode base color, then composites the emphasis result on top:

```ts
const linkColor = useCallback(
  (link: ForceGraphLink): string => {
    // ── Step 1: view-mode base color ──
    let restingColor: string;
    if (viewMode === "mesh") {
      restingColor = LINK_COLOR;
    } else {
      // Pathway + Signal: Terra (unidirectional) or Lumen (bidirectional)
      restingColor = link.bidirectional ? LUMEN_LINK : TERRA_LINK;
    }

    // In Signal mode, further gate: only active-path links are visible at rest.
    // Non-path links are transparent at rest and dim on hover.
    if (viewMode === "signal") {
      const isActive = activePathLinkIdsRef.current.has(
        `${getLinkNodeId(link.source)}::${getLinkNodeId(link.target)}`
      );
      if (!isActive) restingColor = "rgba(0,0,0,0)"; // fully transparent
    }

    // ── Step 2: emphasis composite (topology-invariant) ──
    const emphasis = getLinkEmphasis(
      link,
      hoveredNodeRef.current,
      connectedLinkIdsRef.current,
    );

    switch (emphasis) {
      case "emphasized":
        // Glow color for this link's semantic family
        if (viewMode === "mesh") return LINK_COLOR;          // width carries the emphasis; color stays neutral
        return link.bidirectional
          ? LUMEN_LINK_EMPHASIS_GLOW
          : TERRA_LINK_EMPHASIS_GLOW;
      case "dimmed":
        return LINK_COLOR_DIM;
      case "resting":
        return restingColor;
    }
  },
  [viewMode],
  // ↑ refs are intentionally not in deps — they are read per-frame, not on render
);

const linkWidth = useCallback(
  (link: ForceGraphLink): number => {
    const emphasis = getLinkEmphasis(
      link,
      hoveredNodeRef.current,
      connectedLinkIdsRef.current,
    );
    switch (emphasis) {
      case "emphasized": return LINK_EMPHASIS_WIDTH;
      case "dimmed":     return LINK_WIDTH_DIM;
      case "resting":    return viewMode === "signal"
        ? SIGNAL_ACTIVE_WIDTH
        : LINK_WIDTH;
    }
  },
  [viewMode],
);

// Particle color now also respects hover — particles only visible on emphasized/resting links.
const linkParticleColor = useCallback(
  (link: ForceGraphLink): string => {
    const emphasis = getLinkEmphasis(
      link,
      hoveredNodeRef.current,
      connectedLinkIdsRef.current,
    );
    // On hover: only connected links show particles.
    if (emphasis === "dimmed") return "rgba(0,0,0,0)";     // invisible = no particles
    // Otherwise use the semantic color for this link family:
    return link.bidirectional ? LUMEN_ARROW : TERRA_ARROW;
  },
  [], // view-mode-agnostic
);
```

Wire `linkParticleColor` into the `<ForceGraph2D>` JSX:
```tsx
linkDirectionalParticleColor={linkParticleColor}
```

### Part 4 — Unify `nodeCanvasObject`

The node paint callback currently has view-branching for the dim pass. Replace the branched dim logic with:

```ts
// Inside nodeCanvasObject, after computing baseColor and radius:

const emphasis = getNodeEmphasis(node, hoveredNodeRef.current, connectedNodeIdsRef.current);

// Apply emphasis alpha on top of whatever the view-mode painted:
if (emphasis === "dimmed") {
  ctx.globalAlpha = 0.15;   // dim non-connected nodes uniformly across all views
} else if (emphasis === "emphasized") {
  ctx.globalAlpha = 1.0;    // already painted at full — no change needed
}
// "resting" = no hover active, leave globalAlpha as-is from the view paint pass
```

This ensures that regardless of which view mode chose the node color, the emphasis dim is always applied identically.

---

## Files Changed

| File | Change |
|---|---|
| `src/components/ui/ForceGraph/ForceGraph.tsx` | Add `HoverEmphasis` type + `getLinkEmphasis` + `getNodeEmphasis` helpers; add `connectedLinkIdsRef` + `connectedNodeIdsRef`; rewrite `handleNodeHover` to populate both sets; unify `linkColor`, `linkWidth`, `linkParticleColor` callbacks; unify `nodeCanvasObject` dim pass |

No other files need to change. The playground page and all external consumers are unaffected — the `ForceGraphProps` interface is unchanged.

---

## Principle

**The architectural rule to prevent this drifting again:**

> **Hover emphasis is topology-invariant.** It depends only on two inputs — the hovered node ID and the graph's edge list — and is entirely independent of which view mode is active. View mode controls *what* gets drawn (colors, arrows, particles, opacity tiers). Emphasis controls *how much* of it is shown (dim, normal, bright). These are orthogonal concerns. They must live in separate functions. The emphasis layer is always composited on top of the view-mode layer, never merged into it.
>
> Operationally: any time you add a new view mode or change a view-mode's base color, you must not touch the `getLinkEmphasis` / `getNodeEmphasis` functions. Conversely, any time you change the hover interaction (thresholds, animation, dim opacity), you must not add a `viewMode` branch — the change applies to all views automatically. This is the direct application of the principle from EAP-124 (never let view-local concerns corrupt shared interaction state) extended one level up: EAP-125 — **view-mode branching inside canvas render callbacks.**

The three concrete checklist items to enforce it on any future ForceGraph work:

1. Every canvas callback (`linkColor`, `linkWidth`, `nodeCanvasObject`, `linkDirectionalParticleColor`) must call `getLinkEmphasis` or `getNodeEmphasis` as its *last* step, never as one branch among several.
2. `getLinkEmphasis` and `getNodeEmphasis` must not import `viewMode` — if you find yourself passing `viewMode` to them, you've merged the concerns again.
3. `handleNodeHover` is the *only* place that writes to `connectedLinkIdsRef` and `connectedNodeIdsRef`. No canvas callback should recompute connectivity inline.

